Jeff playing basketball (P) → Amy playing tennis (Q)

Now, let's consider the opposite scenario of P not happening, which means Jeff did not play basketball. In this case, we cannot directly infer whether Q (Amy playing tennis) happened or not because the original statement only tells us what happens when P is true. It does not provide any information about what happens when P is false.

Therefore, based on the given information alone, we cannot logically infer that if Jeff did not play basketball, then Amy did not play tennis. The relationship between P and Q is not transitive in this context.
